# TCP Repair Server Configuration File
#
# This file contains network configuration for all machines in the cluster.
#
# Format (all lines must have exactly 3 fields for consistent parsing):
#
# Line 1: tc <hw|sw> null
#   - hw: Use hardware TC offload (requires supported NIC)
#   - sw: Use software TC
#   - null: Placeholder for 3 fields consistency (do not change this)
#
# Following lines: machine_id ip_address mac_address
#   - machine_id: Unique numeric identifier for each machine
#   - ip_address: IPv4 address of the machine
#   - mac_address: MAC address of the network interface
#

# TC Configuration: hw for hardware offload, sw for software
tc hw null

# Machine Configuration
# Format: ID IP_ADDRESS MAC_ADDRESS

# Client machine (runs wrk)
14 192.168.1.10 aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:01

# Proxy server (1 machine)
35 192.168.1.35 aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:35

# Backend servers (4 machines required)
30 192.168.1.30 aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:30
31 192.168.1.31 aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:31
33 192.168.1.33 aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:33
34 192.168.1.34 aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:34

# How to find your MAC address:
# Run: ip link show <interface_name>
# Look for: link/ether XX:XX:XX:XX:XX:XX

# How to find your IP address:
# Run: ip addr show <interface_name>
# Or assign one: sudo ip addr add 192.168.11.X/24 dev <interface_name>

# Notes:
# - All machines should be on the same Layer 2 network
# - Machine IDs should be unique
# - The same config file should be used on all servers
# - Blank lines and lines starting with # are ignored
